As for burdensome regulation and goofing off at work, the jury is still out.
But basically we=E2=80=99re seeing a whole lot of things happen that tend t=
o reduce TFP growth but that have nothing to do with slowing technological =
progress! We can invent economically useful stuff just as brilliantly as in=
 the past, but if the above stuff happens, TFP will still slow down.
In fact, in a recent book called =E2=80=9CFully Grown: Why a Stagnant Econo=
my Is a Sign of Success=E2=80=9D, the brilliant growth economist Dietrich V=
ollrath =E2=80=94 whose excellent blog [https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJ=
wlkEtuxSAMRVfzGEb8QmDAoJNuAxHsJrQJRED6lN2XNJblK9myrXODb7jkctkj10bu4tp1oE34r=
hu2hoWcFYuLYLmmggtJwEpgetQkVvdVEHcfN9vKieQ45y0G32JO94IYhRzJaicFIw8MAIPhEmGe=
0X9NHDWFiVPQz1t_QsQU0OIvlisnJJtdWzvqS3y8-GfPpeR3WzHkNIS898a85aULiZZTzqigiiq=
