TnDeFBbY9h__BuwYSlGwnON8sUGyljxnR48aDdXtzBhSH9I-S-lWzKfj1i6mb9AVdMgSI] you =
should absolutely read =E2=80=94 argues that most of the slowdown [https://=
email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJwlkM2OhSAMhZ_mstOA_CgLFrOZ1zAIVZlRMPzcG99-YGyaNi=
cnzUk_ozNsId7qCimjNuZ8X6A8fNIBOUNEJUGcnVXDhOlAGbKKWTLxCbk0rxHg1O5QORZAV1kOZ=
3R2wbcDyinjaFd0HLmhwq4CW7MISdkixGQnRqikdB2fWF2sA29AwRviHTygQ-05X-lFv17Dd-0T=
rCtnb8LZNMOnztkc2pu76rUcx91tMXx8p7sIbwefTnM-EmkEZtIgpwY8EEyxwGIQZOpJr-nEzGi=
tMFgSJqU0C-OMkAkLywQeW8g29KksKWvz26JRVD8h7dVpq3epfT1X4yze5XsGr5cD7AMkP1j_Ec=
0beIgVt511VkQQjgmRFQanD4BGrNVAJaqJNtQrr3zQ--V8RfoHJHiMQQ] in TFP comes from=
 slowing educational attainment, lower geographic mobility and economic dyn=
amism, and and the shift from goods to services.=20
Now, slowing technological progress might cause decreased business dynamism=
 (since less new tech means less fuel for new startups). But in general, mo=
st of these things are not caused by a slowdown in the rate of scientific d=
iscoveries or product innovations. That calls the entire technological stag=
nation theory [https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJwlkD1vhDAMhn_NZQPlGzJkuOW=
6Vp26oZD4jrSQoCQU0V_fUCzLlvz1yo81BV4xHXqNuaAzDOVYQQfY8wylQEJbhjR4p2mPGWUcOc=
0d6UWPfB6eCWAxftYlbYDWbZy9NcXHcC4wwbhAkzYjpowaapnhnFEyEtHbp1XCcd7xp7pkzeY8B=
AsafiAdMQCa9VTKmm_sfqOP6vu-t2YxvzG0Ni618OEzNA8zz819gVSVQ_OW4l6m5j35eqrEUKfc=
WgMRTErSU_GJvKaYEsywxJLWWktaw3puO-ekxYpwpZQdueCE9Fg6LnF343h50TZvYy7Gfp_yKOm=
vmKfaOVPr8_n9UBvLFnw5BghmnMFdYMqF9x_V8IIAqWJ3gymaSCIwIUpVVOwCcZI7jTKFqqKLdS=
voEM20-lDR_gHyAo8H] into question. =20
And it also means that if we see a wave of inventions but slow TFP growth, =
it doesn=E2=80=99t necessarily mean that those inventions didn=E2=80=99t bo=
ost TFP! It could just mean that other things were happening at the same ti=
me that held TFP back. In other words, if college attendance stays flat or =
declines, cities keep excluding newcomers by banning construction, and cons=
umers keep shifting to services, it could be enough to obscure most of the =
impact of a 2020s tech boom. But that doesn=E2=80=99t mean the increase was=
n=E2=80=99t there! Technological innovation might be the only thing prevent=
ing TFP from slowing down even more, or even falling outright.
In fact, I think there=E2=80=99s a fair chance this is what will happen in =
the 2020s. BUT, we should also admit that the future isn=E2=80=99t written =
in stone; TFP has spend up and slowed down before, and it might do so again=
=2E=20
The TFP trend can change quickly
As they say, =E2=80=9CThe trend is your friend til the bend at the end.=E2=
=80=9D Part of the case for future stagnation relies on looking at TFP tren=
ds and predicting that these trends will continue. But that=E2=80=99s not s=
et in stone. For example, in the 1990s and early 2000s, productivity growth=
 accelerated temporarily, to something like its old level. Here, let me bor=
row Dietrich Vollrath=E2=80=99s graph (made from Basu, Fernald and Kimball=
=E2=80=99s data):
Something like that red line could happen again. Maybe for another 10 or 15=
 years, maybe for longer. We just don=E2=80=99t know.
In fact, economists Nicholas Crafts and Terence Mills make exactly this poi=
nt [https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJwlkMmO7CAMRb-m2CViCgULFr15vxExOAndCU=
QMVS9_36TLsuwrWda1jzMV1pQvfaZS0V3mep2gI7zLDrVCRq1AnoPXVGJGGUdec0_kJFEo85IBD=
hN2XXMDdDa7B2dqSPFeYBPjE9q0EYuy1i3W0AlbmCRTBC9PJ4lwdMHmY2uaDxAdaHhBvlIEtOut=
1rM82NeD_uv5Sv-hjSmvXZtcg9uhq7Kn93Dm5Jur4RXqNaw5ves2HOYaYqqDhaF_02U-zD60goK=
mmBLMsMCCCiJHMhomuXt6LxxWhCulnOUTJ0Ri4bnAzwfHx0rH0mypxv2MLh0o6-9Utj652xjK_f=
7cB0eL_YoZorE7-A-Z-uH7x2peIULu3P1sqiaCTJgQpTor9iFxo7uDMoW6o099K-qYzHaG2Nn-A=
hC9k0A] in a recent paper [https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxNkE1uxCAMhU8=
TlhF_YWDBolLVayACnoQ2AQRkqty-ZLIpsvADy3r252yDJZVT51Qbui7Tzgw6wm_doDUo6KhQTP=
CaSswo48hr7omcJArVPAvAbsOmWzkA5WPegrMtpHg1sInxCa0apPSUzYCdIMISMdEnECIf5Amz5=
8BvW3v4ANGBhheUM0VAm15by3VgHwP96uEglzGVpUvrWnhBF_8sa3_6UN1R6zVAthnK-y-Pec0D=
6yKmgX0SiqlCQfdEMMMCCyqIHMlomeTu4b1wWBGulHIzn3ifFAvPBX4MHO8LHesx12bdz-jSjor=
-TnXtlSuNoV4MTC_sRwztNBDtvIG_8bQb8huYWSBC6fC9sU0TQSZMiFIdGLtxXPyuQ5lC3dGn3h=
V1THbNIfb9_gDUjZKB]. They write:
Is the econometric evidence to be preferred to techno-optimism or techno-pe=
ssimism?=E2=80=A6[F]orecast trend TFP growth based on estimated trends over=
 the previous 20- or 25-year window exhibits considerable variation and doe=
s not show monotonic decreases=E2=80=A6
[A]verage realised TFP growth=E2=80=A6over 10 year intervals=E2=80=A6has al=
so varied substantially over time=E2=80=A6[T]hese 10-year-ahead outturns ar=
e not well predicted by recent trend TFP growth. In particular, sharp rever=
sals of medium-term TFP growth performance are not identified in advance. I=
ndeed, forecasting on this basis would have missed the productivity slowdow=
n of the 1970s, the acceleration of the mid-1990s, and the slowdown of rece=
nt years =E2=80=93 in other words, all the major episodes during the period=
! =20
[M]edium-term TFP growth is very unpredictable. Recent performance is not a=
 reliable guide, implying that an econometric estimate of low trend product=
ivity growth currently does not necessarily rule out a productivity surge i=
n the near future. The precedent of the 1990s is witness to this. [Also], a=
 smoothed estimate of trend TFP growth has changed only slowly over time an=
d is well above recent actual TFP growth. This suggests that pessimism abou=
t long-term prospects can easily be overdone. =20
In other words:
It=E2=80=99s really hard to predict TFP trends.
If you smooth out the trends, it looks like we=E2=80=99re due for another b=
urst of TFP growth, though really who knows.
In other words, no matter how much evidence you marshal to show that the TF=
P stagnation is real, it might not indicate a technological slowdown, and T=
FP itself might have a boom soon. That doesn=E2=80=99t prove that techno-op=
timism is justified for the 2020s. But it means that looking at recent TFP =
trends and saying =E2=80=9CSee? Stagnation is our destiny!=E2=80=9D is defi=
nitely not warranted.=20
In fact, in Tyler Cowen=E2=80=99s 2011 book The Great Stagnation [https://e=
mail.mg2.substack.com/c/eJwlkctuwyAQRb8m7GzxMoEFi1bqY9EuqnyAhWHi0NhgAa7lfn1=
xg9AdidHVnTlYU2CMaddLzAUd0pd9AR1gyxOUAgmtGVLvnaYSM8o4cpo7IjuJfO6vCWA2ftIlrY=
